Stochastic SIR model using odin

Thibaut Jombart, Rich FitzJohn

2018-10-02

Basic model

The stochastic equivalent of the previous model can be formulated in odin as follows:

model_file <- "odin_model.R"
## Core equations for transitions between compartments:
update(S) <- S - n_SI
update(I) <- I + n_SI - n_IR
update(R) <- R + n_IR

## Individual probabilities of transition:
p_SI <- 1 - exp(-beta * I / N) # S to I
p_IR <- 1 - exp(-gamma) # I to R

## Draws from binomial distributions for numbers changing between
## compartments:
n_SI <- rbinom(S, p_SI)
n_IR <- rbinom(I, p_IR)

## Total population size
N <- S + I + R

## Initial states:
initial(S) <- S_ini
initial(I) <- I_ini
initial(R) <- 0

## User defined parameters - default in parentheses:
S_ini <- user(1000)
I_ini <- user(1)
beta <- user(0.2)
gamma <- user(0.1)

We can use the same workflow as before to run the model, using 10 initial infected individuals (I_ini = 10):

sir_generator <- odin::odin(model_file, verbose = FALSE)
sir_generator
## function (S_ini = NULL, I_ini = NULL, beta = NULL, gamma = NULL, 
##     user = list(S_ini = S_ini, I_ini = I_ini, beta = beta, gamma = gamma)) 
## <an 'odin_generator' function>
##   use coef() to get information on user parameters
x <- sir_generator(I_ini = 10)
set.seed(1)
sir_col <- c("#8c8cd9", "#cc0044", "#999966")

res <- x$run(0:100)
par(mar = c(4.1, 5.1, 0.5, 0.5), las = 1)
matplot(res[, 1], res[, -1], xlab = "Time", ylab = "Number of individuals",
        type = "l", col = sir_col, lty = 1)
legend("topright", lwd = 1, col = sir_col, legend = c("S", "I", "R"), bty = "n")

An example of stochastic, discrete-time SIR model

This gives us a single stochastic realisation of the model, which is of limited interest.

Generating replicates

Stochastic models become interesting when multiple replicates (i.e. independent stochastic realisations of the model) can be generated. odin implements a straightforward interface for this, which we illustrate below.

First, let’s have a look at the arguments of the run function of our new object:

args(x$run)
## function (step, y = NULL, ..., use_names = TRUE, replicate = NULL) 
## NULL

replicate can take an integer indicating the number of independent realisations of the model we are after. Let’s start with 200:

res_200 <- x$run(0:100, replicate = 200)
dim(res_200)
## [1] 101   4 200

res_200 is now a 3-dimensional array storing results for all time steps, compartments and replicates. The function x$transform_variables will be very handy to reformat these results into something we can plot and analyse:

res_200 <- x$transform_variables(res_200)
class(res_200)
## [1] "list"
length(res_200)
## [1] 4
names(res_200)
## [1] "t" "S" "I" "R"
dim(res_200[[1]])
## NULL

res_200 is now a list where every compartment is stored separately; this can be easily coerced into a data.frame for further plotting:

res_200 <- cbind.data.frame(t = res_200[[1]], res_200[-1])
dim(res_200)
## [1] 101 601
res_200[1:10, 1:4]
##    t  S.1  S.2  S.3
## 1  0 1000 1000 1000
## 2  1  999  999  996
## 3  2  998  995  993
## 4  3  996  992  986
## 5  4  995  989  983
## 6  5  992  984  981
## 7  6  991  981  978
## 8  7  986  977  975
## 9  8  984  974  972
## 10 9  978  971  969

Let us define colors for our plot:

## function to make colors transparent, stolen from adegenet::transp
transp <- function (col, alpha = 0.5) {
    res <- apply(col2rgb(col), 2,
                 function(c) rgb(c[1]/255, c[2]/255, 
                                 c[3]/255, alpha))
    return(res)
}

col <- rep(transp(sir_col, .1), each = 200)
par(mar = c(4.1, 5.1, 0.5, 0.5), las = 1)
matplot(res_200[, 1], res_200[, -1], xlab = "Time", ylab = "Number of individuals",
        type = "l", col = col, lty = 1)
legend("topright", lwd = 1, col = sir_col, legend = c("S", "I", "R"), bty = "n")

A handy wrapper for replicates

The steps illustrated in the previous section can be wrapped into a simple function:

## x: instance of odin model
## t: time steps
## n: number of replicates
run_model <- function(x, t = 0:100, n = 1, ...) {
    res <- x$run(t, replicate = n, ...)
    res <- x$transform_variables(res)
    res <- cbind.data.frame(t = res[[1]], res[-1])
    attr(res, "n_compartments") <- length(x$names) - 1
    attr(res, "n_replicates") <- n
    attr(res, "compartments") <- x$names[-1]
    class(res) <- c("pretty_odin", class(res))
    res
}

sir_pal <- colorRampPalette(sir_col)

plot.pretty_odin <- function(x, pal = sir_pal, ...) {
    ## handle colors
    n_compartments <- attr(x, "n_compartments")
    n_replicates <- attr(x, "n_replicates")
    col_leg <- pal(n_compartments)
    alpha <- max(10 / n_replicates, 0.01)
    col <- rep(transp(col_leg, alpha), each = n_replicates)

    ## make plot
    par(mar = c(4.1, 5.1, 0.5, 0.5), las = 1)
    matplot(x[, 1], x[, -1], xlab = "Time", ylab = "Number of individuals",
            type = "l", col = col, lty = 1, ...)
    legend("topright", lwd = 1, col = col_leg, bty = "n",
           legend = attr(x, "compartments"))
}

Here are two examples with 20 time steps, 50 simulations:

plot(run_model(x, t = 0:20, n = 50))

and another one using 100 timesteps and 500 replicates:

plot(run_model(x, t = 0:100, n = 500))
